  <data name="anzFreqExplainer" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Average loudness at each frequency across the whole track. A lossy MP3 usually low-passes the top end, leaving a sharp cut-off cliff whose position hints at the bitrate (~16 kHz ≈ 128k, ~19 kHz ≈ 256k, ~20 kHz ≈ 320k). But high-bitrate AAC or Opus can reach the very top with no cliff, so a full spectrum does not prove lossless: the file format decides that. The amber line marks the detected cut-off.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="anzInfoVerdictHdr" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Quality verdict</value>
  </data>
  <data name="anzInfoVerdictBody" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The coloured badge shows the verdict and animates by tier: a flowing light border for true lossless, a pulsing glow for lossy. The file format settles lossy versus lossless: MP3, AAC and Opus are lossy by definition and can never be truly lossless, however clean they look; only FLAC, ALAC and WAV are. 'Lossy source in a lossless container' means a FLAC or ALAC actually built from an MP3, so the wrapper claims lossless but the audio underneath is not.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="anzInfoWaveformBody" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Loudness over time. Tall sections are loud, thin sections are quiet. Handy for spotting silence, fade-outs, or a brick-walled master that fills the whole height with no dynamics left.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="anzInfoFreqBody" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Average loudness at each frequency across the whole track (there is no time on this graph). A lossy MP3 usually discards the highest frequencies, leaving a sharp cliff whose position hints at the bitrate:</value>
  </data>
  <data name="anzInfoFreqBox" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>~16 kHz  ≈  128 kbps
~19 kHz  ≈  256 kbps
~20 kHz  ≈  320 kbps
(MP3 guides; AAC and Opus keep more)</value>
  </data>
  <data name="anzInfoFreqAfter" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>High-bitrate AAC and Opus can reach the very top with no cliff, so full bandwidth does not prove lossless. The amber line marks the detected cut-off.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="anzInfoSpectroBody" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The same frequencies, but over time: left to right is time, bottom to top is frequency, and colour is loudness (see the legend on the right). A lossy file shows a hard dark ceiling where the encoder cut the highs; lossless fills right to the top. Use the colour-theme dropdown to pick whichever reads clearest for you.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="anzInfoGoodHdr" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Good to know</value>
  </data>
  <data name="anzInfoGoodBody" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The format has the final word on lossy versus lossless; the spectrum only describes bandwidth. A full spectrum does not prove lossless (a good lossy encoder reaches the top too), and a sparse acoustic track or old master can lack highs without being lossy. The spectrogram shows which is which: a hard, flat cliff is a filter (lossy), a gentle natural roll-off is just the music.</value>
  </data>
